In contrast, a major shock event, like the 2022 BCG stockout, could slash the 2030 volume to only 135,000 doses."},{"type":"image","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"40deda13-d17b-458c-9e66-60325cb6e546","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false},"imgFile":"utilization_scenarios_PENTA3.png","imgStretch":true,"imgFit":"inside"}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Sustained IFISH Accelerated Implementation gains could deliver 263,000 Penta3 doses in 2030"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"Following the 2022 stockout, the IFISH Accelerated Implementation period drove a rapid recovery and steady growth in BCG vaccinations from 2023 onwards.

If this trajectory is maintained, the number of BCG vaccinations given in 2030 is projected to reach 275,000—a 10% increase from the 2025 baseline of approximately 250,000.

By contrast, a disruption similar to 2022 would reduce annual BCG vaccinations to just 150,000."},{"type":"image","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"1fed8929-2500-4079-81f0-1ab4a8a0f163","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false},"imgFile":"utilization_scenarios_BCG.png","imgStretch":true,"imgHeight":100,"imgFit":"inside"}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"By 2030, BCG vaccinations could reach 275,000—or collapse to just 150,000"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"On the IFISH Accelerated Implementation trajectory, institutional deliveries by skilled birth attendants would grow by more than 55% from 2025 to 2030, reaching about 248,000 deliveries in 2030 alone.

By contrast, staying on the COVID-19 trajectory would bring only modest gains—a 9% increase by 2030, to around 172,000 deliveries.

The Health Worker Loss scenario would drive a steep decline—by 2030, institutional deliveries would fall to just 110,000."},{"type":"image","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"5a53efc1-d170-4285-bf1e-4d9b37cba5d9","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false},"imgFile":"utilization_scenarios_DELIVERY.png","imgStretch":true,"imgFit":"inside"}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Sustaining IFISH Accelerated Implementation momentum means 55% more safe deliveries by 2030"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"Following stagnation in the post-Ebola years, Penta1 utilization picked up during COVID and accelerated rapidly under IFISH Accelerated Implementation.

If this trajectory continues, the number of Penta1 vaccinations given in 2030 is projected to reach 265,000—an increase of 10% from the 2025 baseline of approximately 250,000.

By contrast, a disruption on the scale of the 2022 BCG stockout would reduce annual Penta1 vaccinations to just 150,000."},{"type":"image","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"1fed8929-2500-4079-81f0-1ab4a8a0f163","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false},"imgFile":"utilization_scenarios_PENTA1.png","imgStretch":false,"imgFit":"inside"}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Sustained momentum could deliver 265,000 Penta1 doses in 2030; disruption could cut this to 150,000"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":3,"markdown":"Most indicators achieve >95% completeness at the national level, indicating that facilities are consistently submitting monthly data across all indicators.

Most counties report near-complete data across indicators, with only minimal gaps observed.

Montserrado and Margibi show some gaps in completeness, pointing to areas for targeted improvement."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.7,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"c20f1672-edfc-4140-ae2c-09a30b50443a","moduleId":"m001","selectedReplicantValue":""}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Reporting completeness"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":3,"markdown":"Nationally, fewer than 1% of facility-months are flagged as outliers, showing that unusually high values are very uncommon in Liberia’s HMIS data.

Most indicators and counties show 0% outliers, with only a handful of small, isolated deviations (e.g., contraception in Lofa, OPD <5 in Gbarpolu).

No county shows a systemic pattern of outliers, with nearly all indicators consistently reporting within expected ranges."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.6,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"c3cb0cc9-4352-4b27-8532-f18e465faec8","moduleId":"m001","selectedReplicantValue":""}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Outliers"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":3,"markdown":"ANC1 vs ANC4 is mostly consistent, though a few counties (Grand Gedeh, Maryland, Rivercess, Sinoe) fall below 90%, suggesting misreporting in one of the indicators.

Delivery vs BCG is weak in many counties, likely influenced by ~19% of births at home; home-born infants later vaccinated can make BCG counts exceed deliveries.

Penta1 vs Penta3 is variable, with some counties >90% but others near 60%, pointing to gaps in recording successive doses."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"cf5b8649-93c2-4bbe-8f2d-773f42ce8ec3","moduleId":"m001","selectedReplicantValue":""}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Internal consistency"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":3,"markdown":"National overall scores remain modest (61–72%), showing that only a limited share of facility-months meet all data quality criteria at the same time.

Performance varies widely across counties: some (e.g., Bomi, Bong, Lofa, Nimba) regularly exceed 80%, while others (e.g., Montserrado, River Gee, Rivercess, Sinoe) often remain below 60%.

Improvements are visible in several counties by 2025 (e.g., Bomi, Grand Cape Mount, Nimba), but persistent gaps remain."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"d46e1957-09dd-41c3-b7dc-b4409da23bbe","moduleId":"m001","selectedReplicantValue":""}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Trends in data quality"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":3,"markdown":"National mean scores are high (90–95%), showing that on average, Liberia’s HMIS data is close to the desired quality standard.

Most counties consistently perform well, with recent gains in Bomi, Montserrado, and Margibi pushing them above 90% by 2025.

Although many facility-months don’t meet all criteria, they are close on average — suggesting that small improvements in reporting practices could bring most facilities above the threshold."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"4dc02c21-29da-4a01-9812-469deedaaac8","moduleId":"m001","selectedReplicantValue":""}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Trends in data quality"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"County-level ANC1 trends vary: while some counties (e.g., River Gee, Grand Gedeh) continue to experience disruptions into 2024–25, others (e.g., Margibi, Sinoe) show clear surpluses above expected.

These divergent patterns at the subnational level likely offset each other, resulting in the national-level finding of little overall change.

The heterogeneity highlights the importance of county-level analysis to identify where recovery is strong versus where gaps remain."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.8,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"845b2531-df94-4dd9-817b-1902e59f2257","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Subnational ANC1 trends are mixed, with disruptions in some counties and surpluses in others"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"Diarrhea and pneumonia cases have remained well below expected levels since late 2023, with prolonged disruptions through 2024.

In early 2025, some rebound is visible, especially for pneumonia, but volumes are still 15.9% lower for diarrhea (~13,300 fewer cases) and 22.8% lower for pneumonia (~22,300 fewer cases) compared to expectations.

The parallel declines across both indicators suggest broader child health service or reporting gaps, raising concerns that children may not be accessing the care they need rather than isolated fluctuations."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.8,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"d7d1c155-d4cd-47ef-8dda-ceea90abf28e","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Child illness cases have remained below expected levels since 2023, with only partial rebound in 2025"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"OPD new cases >5 years: After some disruptions in 2023, volumes rose steadily through 2024 and into 2025, reaching a clear surplus by mid-2025 (≈ 9% above expected, ~102,000 additional cases).

OPD new cases <5 years: Trends are flatter, with modest disruptions in late 2023 and small surpluses emerging in 2025 (≈ 5% above expected, ~23,000 additional cases).

OPD visits are stabilizing, with both age groups showing recovery by 2025, though the rebound is more pronounced among older children and adults than under-fives."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.8,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"30608f3a-f447-4445-be1a-44e1cd8bb73c","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"OPD visits rose above expected levels in 2025, with a stronger rebound among older children and adults than under-fives."}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"Deliveries: Stable through 2023–24, followed by a clear surplus in early 2025, with ~4,900 more facility deliveries than expected (+6.7%).

PNC visits: Multiple disruptions below expected levels in 2023–24, followed by an increase in 2025 that brings volumes closer to or above expected trends.

Because PNC typically follows delivery trends, we would expect these indicators to move together — and in 2025, we see deliveries rising modestly while PNC shows a stronger rebound after earlier disruptions."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"5a53efc1-d170-4285-bf1e-4d9b37cba5d9","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Deliveries show surplus in 2025, while PNC recovers after earlier disruptions"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","span":3,"markdown":"Adolescent FP counseling is stable, averaging 25k–30k contacts/month, with only one notable >10% increase in March 2025.

Modern contraception (new & continuing users) is more volatile, fluctuating 5.5k–8.5k/month with multiple >10% surges (Sep 2023, Aug–Sep 2024, Nov 2024, Jan 2025) and frequent declines.

Overall, counseling is steady, while contraceptive uptake is more sensitive to shifts in program or demand.","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"526bdc78-0d59-4e76-a1d5-b96e11107ff4","moduleId":"m003","isDefault":false,"selectedReplicantValue":""}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Month-to-month change in service volume Adolescent family planning indicators","useFooter":false,"footerText":""}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"Malaria rapid diagnostic tests positive (RDT+): Volumes fell well below expectations in 2022–2023, then showed surpluses in 2023–2024, likely linked to outbreaks. In early 2025, they remain 5.5% below expected (≈ 8,900 fewer cases).

Treatment <24 hrs: Mirrors RDT+, with shortfalls in 2022–2023, partial recovery in 2024, and early 2025 still 10.9% below expected (≈ 13,700 fewer cases).

Even after adjusting for seasonality, malaria services show prolonged disruptions followed by volatile rebounds, with 2025 shortfalls signaling ongoing challenges in malaria service delivery."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.8,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"2cdad879-38a5-4983-8caa-197a8430be18","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Malaria testing and treatment remain below expected levels in early 2025, with shortfalls persisting beyond seasonal patterns"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","span":3,"markdown":"Analysis of antenatal care visit trends highlights that ANC1 shows more frequent and larger month-to-month shifts, with both increases (green) and decreases (red) exceeding 10%. In contrast, ANC4 volumes are more stable, with fewer months registering meaningful changes above the 10% threshold.

